    <text type="letter">
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc.01147.001_large.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place" rend="right">Esopus, <choice>
                            <abbr>NY</abbr><expan>New York</expan></choice>,</name>
                    <date when="1883-08-17" rend="right"><choice>
                            <abbr>Aug</abbr>
                            <expan>August</expan>
                        </choice> 17, <choice>
                            <abbr>83</abbr>
                            <expan>1883</expan>
                        </choice></date>
                </dateline>
                <salute>Dear Walt:</salute>
            </opener>

            <p>Drop me a line where &amp; how you are, &amp; what your plans are for the fall.</p>

            <p>We are just back from Roxbury where we went in July. We are all pretty well. I <choice>
                    <abbr>rec'd</abbr>
                    <expan>received</expan>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <orig>Dr Buckes</orig>
                    <reg>Dr.Bucke's</reg>
                </choice> book &amp; thank you for it. I had already purchased &amp; read it. I
                cannot say that I care <pb xml:id="leaf001v" facs="loc.01147.002_large.jpg"
                    type="verso"/> much for what <choice>
                    <orig>Dr</orig>
                    <reg>Dr.</reg>
                </choice> Bucke has to say; he gives me no new hint or idea. <choice>
                    <abbr>Wm O'Connors</abbr>
                    <expan>William O'Connor's</expan>
                </choice> letter is a treat, with a little too much seasoning. If <choice>
                    <abbr>W<hi rend="superscript"><hi rend="underline">m</hi></hi></abbr>
                    <expan>William</expan>
                </choice> would only practice a little more self-denial, he would be much more
                effective. He <hi rend="underline">could</hi> write so that his critics could not
                laugh at him.</p>
            <p>The review of the book in the <hi rend="underline">Tribune</hi>, was
                by a woman&#8212;a Miss H&#8212;(I forget her name) regularly <pb
                    xml:id="leaf002r" facs="loc.01147.003_large.jpg" type="recto"/> employed upon the paper. The
                latter part of June Gilder &amp; I went to Concord &amp; spent a couple of days there,
                called on <choice>
                    <abbr>Mrs</abbr>
                    <expan>Mrs.</expan>
                </choice> Emerson, liked her much, supped &amp; breakfasted with Sanborn &amp; had
                a pleasant time. Young <choice>
                    <orig>Dr</orig>
                    <reg>Dr.</reg>
                </choice> Emerson, seems a worthy son of his father. I liked him much.</p>

            <p>If we ever get another girl in this house &amp; the kitchen machinery running
                smoothly again, I shall come for you &amp; take no denial. I think it would <pb
                    xml:id="leaf002v" facs="loc.01147.004_large.jpg" type="verso"/> lengthen my days
                to see you once more.</p>

            <closer>
                <salute rend="middle">With love</salute>
                <signed rend="right">John Burroughs</signed>
            </closer>
